How Road Safety Intelligence System saves lives and lays 
the groundwork for fully autonomous transport systems down the road.

üöò System Name: RSIS ‚Äî Road Safety Intelligence System
Purpose

RSIS 3.0 QLN is a full-stack, real-time road safety intelligence system designed to prevent accidents and enhance situational

awareness for vehicles, pedestrians, cyclists, and passengers. It tracks actors on a geospatial grid of hazard tiles, 

calculating dynamic risk scores based on positions, speeds, and role priorities while predicting imminent collisions 

using Time-to-Collision (TTC) metrics. The server, built on Node.js with Express and Socket.IO, handles secure user 

authentication via bcrypt-hashed passwords and JWT tokens, manages ephemeral tokens and trust scores for privacy and 

behavioral monitoring, and aggregates historical risk and incident data to compute predictive probabilities.

The React Native client visualizes hazard tiles on maps with color-coded intensity, lists nearby actors with 

role and speed, and delivers audio and text-to-speech alerts for high-risk zones. Additional features include 

persistent data storage for adaptive learning, simulation scripts for testing, cross-platform deployment, 

and modular services for risk scoring, hazard aggregation, TTC prediction, incident logging, and TTS/audio alerts. 

Overall, RSIS 3.0 QLN is a comprehensive, privacy-conscious predictive safety ecosystem capable of real-time monitoring, hazard detection,

alerting, and long-term trend analysis. ‚Äî Next-Generation Road Safety Intelligence System is an A hybrid AI-

and GPS- guided vehicle behavioral tracking,

and accident-prevention analytics safety platform designed to reduce accidents and fatalities while preparing for fully 

autonomous transport. It continuously monitors driver behavior (speed, lane alignment, 

sudden maneuvers), location, and environmental hazards, providing real-time audio alerts

and corrective feedback. Repeated violations are logged, contribute to a digital driving 

score.

RSIS aggregates anonymized, regional driving data to identify accident-prone areas, dangerous intersections, 

and traffic patterns, enabling infrastructure improvements and road redesigns. The system integrates multi-agent 

tracking for vehicles, pedestrians, cyclists, and mobility aids using GNSS, cellular networks, C-V2X/DSRC, 

BLE beacons, UWB/RTK, and roadside sensors. On-device sensor fusion calculates risk, Time-to-Conflict (TTC), 

and collision probabilities, triggering alerts and coordinated evasive actions. Pedestrian/cyclist-specific 

features prioritize vulnerable users and crosswalk detection.

Privacy is preserved via pseudonymous tokens, local-first policies, and differential privacy in analytics. 

Security includes mutual attestation, spoofing detection, and trust scoring. The UX minimizes alert fatigue 

through prioritization and personalization. RSIS is designed to scale in phased implementations: V2V core,

smartphone/bike modules, infrastructure augmentation, and full integration with DMV, city planners, and emergency response.

Safety impact projections: With partial deployment (20% reduction in fatalities), RSIS could save tens of 
thousands of U.S. lives annually (~238,000 worldwide). Full adoption (50% reduction) could prevent ~20,000 U.S. 
deaths yearly, while also preventing countless non-fatal injuries. 
Real-world effectiveness depends on penetration, compliance, 
false-positive management, legal frameworks, and infrastructure support.

Overall: RSIS provides a real-time, privacy-conscious, multi-agent safety network with predictive analytics, 
enforcement integration, and groundwork for future autonomous vehicles, aiming to transform road safety globally

‚öôÔ∏è System Overview

RSIS is a vehicle-integrated AI and GPS computer that continuously monitors a driver‚Äôs:

Speed

Location

Driving behavior (sudden stops, swerves, etc.)

Environmental hazards (traffic, construction, pedestrians, weather)

It connects to a central national database that records anonymized traffic data and automatically updates maps, 
speed limits, and accident-prone zones.

üì° Core Components

1. Smart GPS Tracker

Installed on every vehicle (or through smartphone integration for older vehicles).

Tracks position, velocity, acceleration, and lane alignment.

This system has potential to be upgraded to one day detect when a driver exceeds speed limits or violates traffic laws.

Provides audio corrections via car speakers:

‚ÄúSlow down, sharp curve ahead.‚Äù

‚ÄúYield ‚Äî pedestrian detected on right.‚Äù

‚ÄúCaution: Work zone approaching.‚Äù

‚ÄúHeavy traffic ahead ‚Äî reducing suggested speed.‚Äù

2. Behavioral Enforcement

If repeated violations occur, the system logs the data and automatically reports digital score.

Violations contribute to a digital driving score.

Drivers who consistently ignore warnings may face:

License review or temporary suspension.

Mandatory digital safety re-training modules.

3. AI-Driven Road Learning

RSIS aggregates regional driving data to detect:

Frequent accident spots.

Dangerous intersections.

Speeding clusters or confusing signage areas.

It then recommends city-level fixes:

‚ÄúLower speed limit by 5 mph on Main Street.‚Äù

‚ÄúAdd signal delay at crosswalk #47.‚Äù

‚ÄúIncrease road visibility near Exit 12.‚Äù

This feedback loop helps engineers redesign roads based on real-world behavior ‚Äî creating safer cities over time.

4. Public Safety and Privacy

All personal identifiers are encrypted.

Only driving scores and violation summaries are visible to authorities.

Anonymized data trains the AI system for:

Safer GPS guidance.

Accident prediction models.

Enhanced maps for future self-driving car networks.

5. Upgrade Path to Self-Driving

RSIS is the foundation for Level-5 autonomous systems:

It studies real human driving errors and learns to avoid them.

When self-driving vehicles dominate the roads, RSIS data will already map:

Human error patterns.

Complex intersections.

Behavior-triggered collisions.

